<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Master the Village vs. Premier vs. Grand Cru Hierarchy</strong> - Burgundy's classification system directly impacts value and drinking windows. Village wines (like Gevrey-Chambertin) are ready in 3-7 years and offer the best introduction to a producer's style. Premier Crus need 5-10 years to show their terroir complexity, while Grand Crus like Chambertin or Montrachet can evolve for 15-30 years. Always check the classification level on the label—it's your roadmap to proper cellaring and expectations.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve Red Burgundy Cooler Than Bordeaux</strong> - Pinot Noir's delicate structure shines at 60-62°F (15-17°C), significantly cooler than most reds. At this temperature, burgundy's signature earthy undertones, bright acidity, and silky tannins are perfectly balanced. Too warm, and the alcohol dominates the wine's elegant aromatics. Place bottles in the refrigerator for 30 minutes before serving, or use a wine thermometer to hit the sweet spot.</li>

  <li><strong>Decant Only Aged Reds and Skip It for Whites</strong> - Young red burgundy (under 8 years) rarely needs decanting—its transparent, food-friendly nature is part of its charm. However, wines over 10 years may have developed sediment and benefit from gentle decanting 30 minutes before serving. White burgundy should never be decanted as it strips away the wine's mineral precision and can cause premature oxidation of its delicate fruit character.</li>

  <li><strong>Choose Burgundy-Specific Glassware</strong> - Use a large-bowled, thin-rimmed glass with a narrower opening than Bordeaux glasses. The balloon shape concentrates burgundy's ethereal aromatics—think forest floor, rose petals, and spice—while the narrow rim directs these delicate scents to your nose. Avoid thick-rimmed glasses that interfere with the wine's subtle texture and always hand-wash to prevent detergent residue from masking the wine's mineral core.</li>

  <li><strong>Learn Producer Styles Over Appellations</strong> - In Burgundy, the winemaker's philosophy matters more than the village name. Domaine de la Romanée-Conti crafts ethereal, long-lived wines, while Henri Jayer's approach emphasized power and richness. Research whether producers use whole cluster fermentation (adds spice and structure), new oak percentages (higher levels mask terroir), and their harvest philosophy. A great producer can make outstanding wine even from lesser appellations.</li>

  <li><strong>Time White Burgundy Consumption Carefully</strong> - Most white burgundy hits its stride 3-5 years after vintage, when the initial tropical fruit integrates with mineral complexity. Chablis peaks earlier (2-4 years) due to its steel-fermented purity, while Meursault and Puligny-Montrachet can evolve beautifully for 8-12 years. Watch for the honeyed, nutty characteristics that develop with age—signals that premier and grand cru whites are entering their optimal drinking window.</li>

  <li><strong>Store Burgundy Bottles Neck-Down for Aging</strong> - Burgundy's traditional thin bottles and delicate corks make them particularly susceptible to cork failure. Store bottles slightly inverted or completely upside down to keep corks moist and maintain the seal. The wine's naturally high acidity acts as a preservative, but only if oxygen exposure is minimized. Check stored bottles annually for ullage (fill level) and consume any showing significant loss quickly.</li>

  <li><strong>Match Food to Burgundy's Earthy Character</strong> - Red burgundy's earthy, mushroom-laden profile pairs exceptionally with game birds, duck, and dishes featuring fungi like coq au vin or beef bourguignon. The wine's bright acidity cuts through rich sauces while its earthy tannins complement umami flavors. White burgundy's mineral backbone and subtle oak support shellfish, roasted chicken, and cream-based dishes without overwhelming delicate proteins—a perfect marriage of Burgundian terroir and cuisine.</li>
</ol>

  <h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Burgundy's aging potential varies dramatically by classification and producer. <strong>Village-level Burgundies</strong> typically peak within 3-8 years, while <strong>Premier Cru</strong> wines develop beautifully over 8-15 years. The crown jewels—<strong>Grand Cru Burgundies</strong> from producers like Domaine de la Romanée-Conti or Armand Rousseau—can evolve gracefully for 20-30 years or more.</p>

<h3>Evolution in the Cellar</h3>

<p>Young red Burgundy often displays bright cherry and raspberry fruit with firm but elegant tannins. As it ages, the wine undergoes remarkable transformation: primary fruit evolves into complex notes of forest floor, truffle, leather, and dried roses. The silky tannins integrate further, creating Burgundy's signature velvety texture. White Burgundy transforms from crisp citrus and green apple to rich honey, hazelnut, and mineral complexity.</p>

<h3>Optimal Storage Conditions</h3>

<p>Store Burgundy at a consistent <strong>55-58°F (13-14°C)</strong> with 70-75% humidity. Keep bottles on their sides in a dark environment away from vibrations. Burgundy's thin Pinot Noir skins make it particularly sensitive to temperature fluctuations, which can cause premature oxidation.</p>

<h3>Peak Drinking Windows</h3>

<ul>
<li><strong>Bourgogne AOC:</strong> 2-5 years</li>
<li><strong>Village wines:</strong> 4-8 years</li>
<li><strong>Premier Cru:</strong> 6-15 years</li>
<li><strong>Grand Cru:</strong> 10-25+ years</li>
</ul>

<h3>Recognizing Proper Development</h3>

<p>Well-aged Burgundy shows <strong>brick-red edges</strong> in reds and deeper gold in whites. Aromas become more complex and integrated. Warning signs include browning throughout the wine, acetone-like smells, or complete loss of fruit character. The cork should remain moist and intact—a dry, crumbly cork often indicates poor storage conditions that may have compromised the wine's integrity.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between red Burgundy and Pinot Noir from other regions?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Red Burgundy is exclusively Pinot Noir, but it expresses unique characteristics due to Burgundy's limestone-rich soils and continental climate. Burgundian Pinot Noir typically shows more earthy, mineral notes with red fruit flavors, higher acidity, and more structured tannins compared to the riper, fruit-forward styles found in California or the herbaceous qualities of Oregon Pinot Noir. The concept of terroir in Burgundy creates distinct flavor profiles that vary dramatically even between neighboring vineyards.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Burgundy wine good for beginners, or should I start elsewhere?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Burgundy can be challenging for beginners due to its subtle, complex flavors and high prices, but village-level wines like Gevrey-Chambertin or Meursault offer an excellent introduction. Start with entry-level Burgundian producers like Louis Jadot or Joseph Drouhin to understand the region's style without breaking the bank. The wine's elegance and food-friendliness make it very approachable once you develop a palate for more nuanced flavors rather than bold, fruit-forward wines.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Why is Burgundy wine so expensive compared to other French wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Burgundy's high prices stem from extremely limited production due to small vineyard plots (some Grand Cru vineyards are only a few acres), strict appellation laws, and centuries of reputation building. The region's complex classification system creates scarcity—there are only about 30 Grand Cru vineyards in all of Burgundy, producing tiny quantities. Additionally, Burgundy's fragmented ownership means many producers make only a few barrels of each wine, driving up costs through supply and demand economics.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do I choose between white and red Burgundy for a dinner party?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Choose white Burgundy (Chardonnay) for seafood, poultry, cream-based dishes, and cheese courses, as its mineral acidity and subtle oak complement delicate flavors. Red Burgundy pairs beautifully with roasted meats, game, mushroom dishes, and soft cheeses due to its earthy complexity and moderate tannins. For versatility, a white Burgundy like Chablis works with more diverse foods, while a light red Burgundy like Volnay can handle both meat and heartier fish dishes.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between Chablis and other white Burgundy wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Chablis comes from the northernmost part of Burgundy and is made from Chardonnay grown in Kimmeridgian limestone soils, creating wines with pronounced mineral character, crisp acidity, and minimal oak influence. Other white Burgundies from Côte de Beaune areas like Meursault or Puligny-Montrachet typically show richer, more buttery textures with more prominent oak aging and tropical fruit notes. Chablis emphasizes purity and mineral expression, while Côte de Beaune whites focus on richness and complexity.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I decant red Burgundy, and if so, for how long?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Young red Burgundy (under 10 years) benefits from 30-60 minutes of decanting to open up its complex aromatics and soften tannins, while mature Burgundy (15+ years) should be decanted just before serving to avoid over-aeration. The wine's delicate structure means it can lose its elegance quickly if over-exposed to air. For very old Burgundy, use a gentle pour method or brief decanting (10-15 minutes) to separate sediment without sacrificing the wine's fragile bouquet.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibeled text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the best value alternatives to expensive Burgundy wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">For red Burgundy alternatives, look to Oregon Pinot Noir from Willamette Valley, German Spätburgunder, or wines from Burgundy's satellite regions like Mercurey or Givry which offer similar terroir expression at lower prices. For white Burgundy substitutes, consider Chablis Premier Cru over Grand Cru, or explore high-quality Chardonnays from Mâcon-Villages, which share Burgundy's mineral-driven style. Australian Chardonnays from cool climates like Adelaide Hills also provide excellent value with similar elegance and complexity.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when buying Burgundy wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The biggest mistake is not researching the producer—in Burgundy, the winemaker matters more than the vineyard classification, as quality varies dramatically between producers even from the same appellation. Many buyers focus solely on Grand Cru or Premier Cru designations without considering that a skilled winemaker's village-level wine often outperforms a mediocre producer's Premier Cru. Always prioritize reputable producers like Domaine de la Romanée-Conti, Henri Jayer, or Leroy over vineyard classification alone.</p>
